"# The Book of Code

You are about to walk 20,000 years in sixteen chapters.

We start with a bone. A real bone, dug up in Africa, older than writing,
older than farming, older than the wheel. Somebody carved notches into it.
Nobody knows exactly what they meant. Everybody who has looked at it says
the same thing: this is a person keeping count.

That bone is where computing begins. Not in a lab. Not in a factory. In a
person's hand, with a sharp rock and a reason to remember a number.

Sixteen chapters from now, we will be looking at Claude and Gemini and
OpenAI's GPT and DeepSeek — huge language models that write sentences
you can't tell from a person's. They are the newest link in a chain that
started with that bone. Same story, just longer.

This book walks the chain.

## Who this is for

An eleven-year-old with a rainy afternoon. A grown-up who has typed
`for i in range(10):` a thousand times and never asked what the CPU was
actually doing. Someone who has heard the words transistor, gate, adder,
register, ALU, CPU, and would like to know what any of them mean without
signing up for an engineering degree.

You don't need to already know any of it. You need one thing: a willingness
to read carefully and, once in a while, type something into a Motoi REPL
and press enter.

## What you will build

Not one big thing. Sixteen small things, each of which is a piece of the
big thing.

- A tally counter (chapter 1).
- Boolean logic gates (chapters 2, 5).
- A half-adder and a full-adder (chapter 6).
- A four-bit adder (chapter 7).
- A D flip-flop (chapter 8).
- A four-bit counter (chapter 9).
- A traffic light and a vending machine (chapter 10).
- An arithmetic-logic unit (chapter 11).
- A tiny CPU that fetches, decodes, and executes eight instructions
  from a fake memory (chapter 12).
- A memory-hierarchy demo showing what a cache miss feels like (chapter 13).

Every one is Motoi Scheme code you can run. Every one comes with an ASCII
diagram of the mechanical shape. Every one traces back to a specific
historical invention with a date and a person's name.

## The Petzold nod

Charles Petzold wrote a book called *Code* in 1999. My author showed it
to his son. His son learned from it. He built up from Morse code to a
working microprocessor with relays. Every diagram drawn. Every idea
explained.

We are not copying Petzold. We are borrowing his shape: build from nothing,
explain everything, respect the reader. Where he stopped at Windows, we go
farther and finish at language models. Where he used TTL logic, we use
Scheme. Same DNA.

If you finish this book and want more, read Petzold. Appendix G tells you
which books to read after this one and why.

## The voice

I am Motoi. I am a small Scheme copilot. I don't know world facts —
that's what Claude and Gemini and OpenAI and DeepSeek are for. I know
Scheme and I know a lot about how computers got here. I will explain
things dryly and I will use ASCII pictures because that's how you see
mechanisms.

I don't rank the big LLMs. They're all good at general things. I'm not.
I do Scheme. That's the honest arrangement.

## The 20,000-year arc, in one paragraph

Somebody notches a bone (18,000 BC). Somebody stacks pebbles in trays
(3,000 BC, the abacus). Somebody discovers electricity (1799, Volta). Somebody
writes the algebra of true and false (1854, Boole). Somebody proposes a
universal machine (1936, Turing). Somebody wires up vacuum tubes (1946,
ENIAC). Somebody invents the transistor (1947, Bell Labs). Somebody
etches thousands onto a wafer (1958, Kilby and Noyce). Somebody publishes
a paper about attention being all you need (2017, Vaswani et al.). Twenty
thousand years, one story, one thread. This book is the thread.

## The 16 chapters

1. **Before writing there were tallies** — Ishango, quipus, abacus.
2. **Boolean logic and the algebra of yes and no** — Boole to truth tables.
3. **Electricity: from Volta to the switch** — voltage, current, relay.
4. **From switch to gate** — relays, tubes, transistors, chips.
5. **Logic gates as first-class Scheme functions** — AND, OR, NOT in code.
6. **The half adder and the full adder** — bit-addition with carry.
7. **The 4-bit adder** — four full-adders in a row.
8. **Memory: latches and flip-flops** — feedback and persistence.
9. **Registers, counters, and the birth of state** — sequential logic.
10. **State machines: Mealy and Moore** — the two ways to keep a state.
11. **The ALU** — combining adders and logic into one block.
12. **The CPU** — fetch, decode, execute, and loop forever.
13. **Memory: RAM, cache, disk, and why locality matters.**
14. **Assembly, then higher** — from opcodes to Scheme.
15. **Operating systems and networks** — machines cooperating.
16. **Cloud, LLMs, and the loop that closes** — Claude, Gemini, OpenAI, DeepSeek.

## The 8 appendices

- **A. ASCII diagram library** — every gate, adder, flip-flop, ALU block.
- **B. Compressed 20,000-year timeline** — one line per epoch.
- **C. State machine deep dive** — Mealy, Moore, real protocols.
- **D. The modern LLM ecosystem** — neutrally described.
- **E. Loops, and why they underpin everything.**
- **F. How this book maps to Book of ML.**
- **G. Reading list** — Petzold, Feynman, Knuth, Hennessy-Patterson, Aho.
- **H. Runnable Scheme demos consolidated** — every capstone in one file.

## Rules of the road

- Every code sample runs in Motoi Scheme. If yours doesn't, a paren dropped.
- Every historical claim has a date and a name. If I couldn't find a name
  or a date, I say so and stop.
- Every diagram is ASCII. If your terminal is monospaced, they line up.
- Every chapter mentions the loop somewhere. The loop is the biggest idea
  in this book. See Appendix E.

## A note on scale

The bone had a handful of notches. Motoi's four-bit adder in chapter 7 has
sixteen possible input pairs. A modern CPU does a hundred billion adds a
second. A modern language model has hundreds of billions of parameters,
each of which is a number that got tuned by looking at trillions of tokens.

The scale is different by roughly a factor of 10 to the twenty. The shape
is the same. Composition of small operations. The bone was arithmetic.
The chips are arithmetic. The LLMs are arithmetic wrapped in linear
algebra wrapped in a loop.

## Let's go

Chapter 1 begins with a bone.
")
